                here</atrbt>
        </lb>
        <lb L="7"> And not <rhyme verb="2">afar.</rhyme></lb>
        <lb L="8"> To help yourself</lb>
        <lb L="9">
            <atrbt element="STAMP">
                <atrbt element="End/Bottom"> RED LIBRARY OF CONGRESS STAMP</atrbt> And your fellow
                    <rhyme verb="3">man,</rhyme></atrbt>
        </lb>
        <lb L="10">Train your head,</lb>
        <lb L="11"> Your heart, and your <rhyme verb="3">hand.</rhyme></lb>
        <!-- on the original document, "and your hand" is underlined. Curious as to why? -->
        <lb L="12"> For smartness alone's</lb>
        <lb L="13"> Surely not <rhyme verb="4">meet</rhyme>— </lb>
        <lb L="14"> If you haven't at the same time</lb>
        <lb L="15"> Got something to <rhyme verb="4">eat.</rhyme></lb>
        <lb L="16"> Thus at Tuskegee </lb>
        <lb L="17"> He built a <rhyme verb="6">school</rhyme></lb>
        <lb L="18"> With book-learning there</lb>
        <lb L="19"> And the workman's <rhyme verb="6">tool.</rhyme></lb>
        <lb L="20"> He started out </lb>
        <lb L="21"> In a simple way—</lb>
        <lb L="22"> For yesterday</lb>
        <lb L="23"> Was not today.</lb>
